2026-04-21 01:27:46 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control Module 6 port_p/port_n output coupling'] hypothesis_explanation='The series 12V path must pass through each control module’s internal coupling between its input (+) and output (+) terminals when the module is wired correctly. The inspection shows that Control Input Cable (+) 6 is correctly joined to Control Output Cable (+) 5 at port ‘p’ of Control Module 6, but that port ‘n’ of Control Module 6 is left floating. This means the outgoing 12V line from Control Module 6 toward Control Module 7 (the cable that should be tied to Input Cable (+) 6 inside CM6) is not actually connected into the series path. As a result, the main supply is open-circuited at CM6, so no current reaches Control Modules 7–8 or the load, preventing any later indicators or the final lamp from turning on. The root cause is a misconnection/open at the output side of Control Module 6 (its port_p/port_n coupling or the wiring that should bridge them). Repairing/reconnecting this output coupling so that the incoming + at CM6 is properly continued to the outgoing + should restore power downstream and allow the lamp to operate when all switches are ON.'
