2026-04-21 01:28:16 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control Module 6 port_p/port_n input cabling configuration (all + and − cables on both faces)'] hypothesis_explanation='The root cause is a cabling/configuration error around Control Module 6, not an internal fault of its output coupling.\n\nFrom the latest observation: on the upstream face of CM6, the + line (Control Input Cable (+)6) is only at port p and is doubled with Control Output Cable (+)5, while port n on that face carries only 0 V lines. Thus the internal series + path: PSU → … → CM5 → CM6 → CM7 is interrupted, because the + entering CM6 at port p is not correctly routed through to the downstream connector in the simple series fashion used by the other modules. Instead, the upstream + is effectively tied together with the previous module’s + (CO(+ )5) and never properly forwarded on its own dedicated through‑connection; meanwhile 0 V is fanned out to multiple terminals. This mis‑wiring at CM6 breaks the main 12 V series path to CM7 and the load, so none of the downstream control‑module LEDs nor the lamp can energize, despite the PSU LED being on.\n\nThe earlier repair attempt targeting only the “port_p/port_n output coupling” was wrong because the problem is not a defective coupling component but the way all four +/− cables are plugged on both faces of CM6. Corrective action is to reconfigure the cabling at CM6 so that, like every other control module, each face has exactly one + and one −, and the + and − each pass straight through the module in series with its internal switch, without doubling or cross‑connecting terminals.'
